	<header class=3D"fl-post-header" role=3D"banner">
		<h1 class=3D"fl-post-title" itemprop=3D"headline">
			How Yeast Pitching Rates Affect Beer Fermentation					</h1>
		<div class=3D"fl-post-meta fl-post-meta-top"><span class=3D"fl-post-autho=
r">By <a href=3D"https://www.precisionfermentation.com/blog/author/api/"><s=
pan>API</span></a></span><span class=3D"fl-sep"> | </span><span class=3D"fl=
-post-date">March 22, 2021</span></div><meta itemscope=3D"" itemprop=3D"mai=
nEntityOfPage" itemtype=3D"https://schema.org/WebPage" itemid=3D"https://ww=
w.precisionfermentation.com/blog/yeast-pitching-rates-beer-fermentation/" c=
ontent=3D"How Yeast Pitching Rates Affect Beer Fermentation"><meta itemprop=
=3D"datePublished" content=3D"2021-03-22"><meta itemprop=3D"dateModified" c=
ontent=3D"2023-09-11"><div itemprop=3D"publisher" itemscope=3D"" itemtype=
=3D"https://schema.org/Organization"><meta itemprop=3D"name" content=3D"Pre=
cision Fermentation"><div itemprop=3D"logo" itemscope=3D"" itemtype=3D"http=
s://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop=3D"url" content=3D"https://www.p=
recisionfermentation.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/precision-fermentation-=
brewmonitor.png"></div></div><div itemscope=3D"" itemprop=3D"author" itemty=
pe=3D"https://schema.org/Person"><meta itemprop=3D"url" content=3D"https://=
www.precisionfermentation.com/blog/author/api/"><meta itemprop=3D"name" con=
tent=3D"API"></div><div itemscope=3D"" itemprop=3D"image" itemtype=3D"https=
://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop=3D"url" content=3D"https://www.pr=
ecisionfermentation.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/yeast-pitching.png"><met=
a itemprop=3D"width" content=3D"690"><meta itemprop=3D"height" content=3D"4=
12"></div><div itemprop=3D"interactionStatistic" itemscope=3D"" itemtype=3D=
"https://schema.org/InteractionCounter"><meta itemprop=3D"interactionType" =
content=3D"https://schema.org/CommentAction"><meta itemprop=3D"userInteract=
ionCount" content=3D"0"></div>	</header><!-- .fl-post-header -->

=09
=09
	<div class=3D"fl-post-content clearfix" itemprop=3D"text">
		<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;"><img fetchpriority=3D"high" decoding=
=3D"async" class=3D"size-medium wp-image-3988 alignright lazy entered loade=
d" src=3D"https://www.precisionfermentation.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/=
yeast-pitch-rate-4-300x200.jpg" data-src=3D"https://www.precisionfermentati=
on.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/yeast-pitch-rate-4-300x200.jpg" alt=3D"Ye=
ast Pitch Rate" width=3D"300" height=3D"200" data-srcset=3D"https://www.pre=
cisionfermentation.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/yeast-pitch-rate-4-300x20=
0.jpg 300w, https://www.precisionfermentation.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/0=
3/yeast-pitch-rate-4.jpg 600w" data-sizes=3D"(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300p=
x" data-ll-status=3D"loaded">Does pitch rate matter? Though not everyone ag=
rees, prevailing wisdom strongly suggests that brewers who prioritize accur=
ate flavors and/or consistency should absolutely pay attention to their yea=
st counts.&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">But how does a brewer calculate what t=
heir target pitch rate should be? And what happens if they over-pitch or un=
der-pitch their yeast? The various factors required to calculate a target p=
itch rate for beer can make figuring out the formula quite complicated. So =
let=E2=80=99s deconstruct the topic and find some easy ways to do it.&nbsp;=
</span></p>
<h3><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">What are Pitching and Target Pitch Ra=
tes?</span></h3>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">The Oxford Companion to Beer defines p=
itching as =E2=80=9Cthe process of adding yeast to wort to start fermentati=
on and produce beer.=E2=80=9D The brewing dictionary advises: =E2=80=9CThe =
term =E2=80=98pitching=E2=80=99 may seem to have connotations of a baseball=
 throw, but it should actually be done gently so as to minimize stress on t=
he yeast and ensure rapid growth.=E2=80=9D</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">A pitch rate is simply the number of y=
east cells added to the fermentation tank per volume of wort. Yeast can be =
added directly to the wort in dry form or via a wet slurry of propagated ye=
ast. Pitch rate calculations vary based on which method is used.&nbsp;&nbsp=
;</span></p>
<h3><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Why is the Target Pitch Rate Importan=
t?</span></h3>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">If you want to brew consistent beers, =
it=E2=80=99s critical to maintain a standard pitch rate each time you make =
the same beer. And as we know, yeast is temperamental. It needs just the ri=
ght conditions to do its work.&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">If you under-pitch, meaning you don=E2=
=80=99t add enough yeast to the cooled wort waiting inside your fermenter, =
the individual yeast cells may struggle to do more work than they can handl=
e. They can reproduce too many times in order to compensate, which increase=
s the chances of off-flavors.&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Low pitch rates raise the odds that fe=
rmentation characteristics like esters will develop. This may or may not be=
 a good thing, depending on your intended style and flavor profile.</span><=
/p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">If you over-pitch, or dump in too much=
 yeast, your squadron of cells might over-accomplish its mission, thereby f=
ermenting too fast and stripping the beer of much of its desired character.=
 If you=E2=80=99re aiming for esters and other complexities that arise duri=
ng fermentation, you might not get them.&nbsp;</span></p>
<h3><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">How Do You Determine Pitch Rate?</spa=
n></h3>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Pitch rate depends on original gravity=
, yeast strain and fermentation temperature. The cooler the fermentation, t=
he slower the yeast activity to start and the more you need to pitch to get=
 the job done. Lagers fall into this category.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Because ales ferment warmer they natur=
ally ferment faster, meaning they don=E2=80=99t require as much yeast to ju=
mp start the process. However, higher concentrations of alcohol =E2=80=94 i=
n both ales and lagers =E2=80=94 can create greater barriers for the yeast =
to overcome. Brewers can adjust for this by pitching at a higher rate.&nbsp=
;</span></p>
<h3><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">What Are Standard Pitch Rates for Bre=
wing Lagers and Ales?</span></h3>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Pitch rates are usually expressed as c=
ells per milliliter. A very broad guideline for pitching yeast is a general=
ly agreed upon 1 million cells per milliliter per degrees Plato. But like a=
lmost everything in brewing, the agreement doesn=E2=80=99t extend much furt=
her than that.&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">In their book, </span><span style=3D"f=
ont-weight: 400;">Yeast</span><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">, for examp=
le, Chris White and Jamil Zainasheff say they prefer 0.75 million c/ml for =
many styles of ales and 1.5 million c/ml for a range of lagers but that eac=
h brewer should determine ideal pitch rates for each unique beer they make.=
 They also note that when pitching a fresh, lab-grown culture, brewers can =
typically expect to be able to cut these pitch rates in half.&nbsp;&nbsp;&n=
bsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">For more precision, most brewers plug =
their numbers into a free online pitch rate calculator. Because yeast brand=
s perform differently from one another, it=E2=80=99s best to use the pitch =
rate calculator provided by your yeast vendor. If you=E2=80=99re relying on=
 a chart or your own calculations, remember that high-alcohol beers and tho=
se fermented with Brettanomyces carry specific considerations.</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">There are several ways to get an accur=
ate cell count of your pitch. Many yeast providers will include a guarantee=
d =E2=80=9Clive cell per milliliter=E2=80=9D with any fresh liquid pitch, o=
r dormant cell per gram for dry yeast. If your brewery propagates its own y=
east, frequently pitches cone-to-cone or from a yeast brink, it=E2=80=99s a=
dvisable to invest in a 40x microscope and a hemocytometer in order to coun=
t cells in house. For those worried about how granular to get when counting=
, don=E2=80=99t self-apply too much pressure. The key, according to White a=
nd Zainasheff, is less about focusing on exact counts of cells and more abo=
ut being consistent with the overall pitch quantity each time you pitch.&nb=
sp;</span></p>
<h3><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">What=E2=80=99s the Difference Between=
 Direct Pitching Yeast and Pitching Propagated Yeast?</span></h3>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Brewers who choose to save money by bu=
ying relatively small amounts of yeast and propagating (AKA =E2=80=9Cgrowin=
g=E2=80=9D) it into larger quantities need to factor in the volume of slurr=
y instead of merely the total volume of wort.&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">In the most common type of propagation=
, called a =E2=80=9C1-Step-10-Fold,=E2=80=9D a brewer inoculates a little b=
it of wort, lets it attenuate 50-75% then adds ten times that amount of oxy=
genated wort on top. According to Wyeast, ales and wheat beers fermented th=
is way call for a pitch rate of 1 liter of yeast per barrel, while lagers a=
nd high-gravity beers do best with double that.&nbsp;</span></p>
<h3><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">What if the Pitch Rate is Wrong?</spa=
n></h3>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Because a low pitch rate creates a hig=
her rate of cell growth, under-pitched beer can develop a host of problems,=
 the worst of which are infections and off-flavors like diacetyl, sulfur, f=
usel alcohol and unwanted esters. Gravities may get too high and a brewer m=
ay end up with a stuck fermentation.&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Over-pitches are much more forgiving, =
although they can lead to uber-fast fermentations, low ester production, th=
in body, and autolysis, which gives the beer an unpleasant yeasty flavor. H=
owever, whereas under-pitching can be corrected by simply adding a bit more=
 yeast, over-pitching is impossible to rectify. So if you=E2=80=99re unsure=
 of the correct volume to pitch, it could be beneficial to aim slightly low=
er, then perform a cell count of the fresh wort, and correct accordingly.</=
span></p>


